A '''lithospheric drip''' is a geological phenomenon in which a dense and relatively cold mass of [[lithosphere]] sinks into the more fluid [[upper mantle]]. The regions of descending material have been detected by [[seismic tomography]] methods and modeled as near vertically oriented cylindrical masses within the upper mantle. The lithospheric drip discovered below the [[Great Basin]] in central [[Nevada]] has dimensions of 100&nbsp;km diameter by 500&nbsp;km vertical length.<ref name=NSF>{{cite news |author=National Science Foundation |date=May 27, 2009 |title=Dripping 'Blob' Under Western U.S.: A Hidden Drip, Drip, Drip Beneath Earth's Surface |url=https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2009/05/090526171813.htm |newspaper=Science Daily |location= |access-date=January 12, 2016 }}</ref><ref name="WestFouch2009">{{cite journal|last1=West|first1=John D.|last2=Fouch|first2=Matthew J.|last3=Roth|first3=Jeffrey B.|last4=Elkins-Tanton|first4=Linda T.|title=Vertical mantle flow associated with a lithospheric drip beneath the Great Basin|url=http://www.anisotropy.net/Download/ngeo526.pdf|access-date=January 12, 2016|journal=Nature Geoscience|volume=2|issue=6|year=2009|pages=439–444|issn=1752-0894|doi=10.1038/ngeo526}}</ref>
Another area underlain by a descending cylindrical mass of dense lithosphere has been reported in the southwestern [[Sierra Nevada (U.S.)|Sierra Nevada]] and portions of the [[San Joaquin Valley]] of California. Here a 100&nbsp;km by 225&nbsp;km mass of relatively high density (fast [[p wave]] velocity) has been discovered below an area of anomalous topography.<ref name="SaleebyFoster2004">{{cite journal|last1=Saleeby|first1=Jason|last2=Foster|first2=Zorka|title=Topographic response to mantle lithosphere removal in the southern Sierra Nevada region, California|url=http://geology.gsapubs.org/content/32/3/245.abstract|access-date=January 12, 2016|journal=Geology|volume=32|issue=3|year=2004|pages=245|issn=0091-7613|doi=10.1130/G19958.1}}</ref>
==References== {{reflist}}
[[Category:Geological processes]] [[Category:Structure of the Earth]]
{{geophysics-stub}}

{{short description|A seismically active zone paralleling the Saint Lawrence River}}
The '''Saint Lawrence rift system''' is a [[Seismology|seismically]] active zone paralleling the [[Saint Lawrence River]]. The [[rift]] system trends northeast and southwest and forms a [[half-graben]] that links the [[Ottawa-Bonnechere Graben|Ottawa-Bonnechere]] and the [[Saguenay Graben|Saguenay]] grabens. The rift system extends more than {{convert|1000|km|abbr=on}} along the Saint Lawrence valley from the [[Ottawa]] – [[Montreal]] area. Within the system, [[Fault (geology)|fault]] reactivation is believed to occur along late [[Proterozoic]] to early [[Paleozoic]] normal faults related to the opening of the [[Iapetus Ocean]].<ref name="SI">{{cite book |first=Alain |last=Tremblay |first2=Yvon |last2=Lemieux |chapter=Supracrustal faults of the St. Lawrence rift system between Cap-Tourmente and Baie-Saint-Paul, Quebec |title=Current Research 2001 |publisher=Natural Resources Canada |isbn=0-662-29890-X |id=M44-2001/D15E-IN |chapterurl=http://dsp-psd.pwgsc.gc.ca/Collection/M44-2001-D15E.pdf |year=2001}}</ref>

Two significant historically active seismic zones occur along this system associated with northwest trending intersecting [[graben]] structures. The [[Charlevoix]] region has been the location of at least five magnitude six or larger [[earthquake]]s over the last 350 years, including the [[1925 Charlevoix–Kamouraska earthquake]]. At the Lower St Lawrence zone the largest recorded earthquakes are about magnitude five. Seismic studies indicate a crustal convergence across the Saint Lawrence valley of about {{convert|.5|mm|abbr=on}} per year.<ref>{{cite web| last=Mazzotti |first=S. |last2=Henton |first2=J. |last3=Adams |first3=J. |title=Crustal strain rates and seismic hazard from seismicity and GPS measurements along the St Lawrence Valley, Quebec |publisher=American Geophysical Union |date=Spring 2004 |id=Abstract #S14A-02 |bibcode=2004AGUSM.S14A..02M}}</ref>

The earthquakes of the [[Charlevoix Seismic Zone]] are thought to be related to the re-activation of ancient fault structures by the [[Charlevoix crater|Charlevoix impact event]].<ref>{{cite journal |first=F. |last=Anglin |first2=G. |last2=Buchbinder |title=Microseismicity in the mid-St. Lawrence Valley Charlevoix zone, Québec |journal=Bulletin of the Seismological Society of America |date=October 1981 |volume=71 |issue=5 |pages=1553–60 |url=http://bssa.geoscienceworld.org/cgi/content/abstract/71/5/1553}}</ref>

